ectively, between each consecutive elements.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: arr = [1,2,4]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: There is no way to reorder the elements to obtain an arithmetic progression.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= arr.length <= 1000`\n\n- `-10⁶ <= arr[i] <= 10⁶`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Sorting"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"A sequence of numbers is called an **arithmetic progression** if the difference between any two consecutive elements is the same.\n\nGiven an array of numbers `arr`, return `true` *if the array can be rearranged to form an **arithmetic progression**. Otherwise, return* `false`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: arr = [3,5,1]\nOutput: true\nExplanation: We can reorder the elements as [1,3,5] or [5,3,1] with differences 2 and -2 respectively, between each consecutive elements.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: arr = [1,2,4]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: There is no way to reorder the elements to obtain an arithmetic progression.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= arr.length <= 1000`\n\n- `-10⁶ <= arr[i] <= 10⁶`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/can-make-arithmetic-progression-from-sequence/","problemName":"Can Make Arithmetic Progression From Sequence","problemNumber":1502,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"A sequence of numbers is called an **arithmetic progression** if the difference between any two consecutive elements is the same.\n\nGiven an array of numbers `arr`, return `true` *if the array can be rearranged to form an **arithmetic progression**. Otherwise, return* `false`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: arr = [3,5,1]\nOutput: true\nExplanation: We can reorder the elements as [1,3,5] or [5,3,1] with differences 2 and -2 respectively, between each consecutive elements.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: arr = [1,2,4]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: There is no way to reorder the elements to obtain an arithmetic progression.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= arr.length <= 1000`\n\n- `-10⁶ <= arr[i] <= 10⁶`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Easy","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"A sequence of numbers is called an **arithmetic progression** if the difference between any two consecutive elements is the same.\n\nGiven an array of numbers `arr`, return `true` *if the array can be rearranged to form an **arithmetic progression**. Otherwise, return* `false`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: arr = [3,5,1]\nOutput: true\nExplanation: We can reorder the elements as [1,3,5] or [5,3,1] with differences 2 and -2 respectively, between each consecutive elements.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: arr = [1,2,4]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: There is no way to reorder the elements to obtain an arithmetic progression.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= arr.length <= 1000`\n\n- `-10⁶ <= arr[i] <= 10⁶`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/can-make-arithmetic-progression-from-sequence/","problemName":"Can Make Arithmetic Progression From Sequence","problemNumber":1502,"problemSlug":"can-make-arithmetic-progression-from-sequence","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":1502,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[{"assetIndex":0,"bytes":49993,"contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1503-last-moment-before-all-ants-fall-out-of-a-plank/1503-ants.jpg","originalUrl":"../../../images/1503-ants.jpg","sha256":"9f26ef75b93b7523dd4c42116abb59641f8e16127bb41f7fa620e6aca0dc9188"},{"assetIndex":1,"bytes":13338,"contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1503-last-moment-before-all-ants-fall-out-of-a-plank/1503-ants2.jpg","originalUrl":"../../../images/1503-ants2.jpg","sha256":"84f78ab599408ebb8dcf6d79b0b14c2e0abc54799530a607f6162367e388f434"},{"assetIndex":2,"bytes":13592,"contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1503-last-moment-before-all-ants-fall-out-of-a-plank/1503-ants3.jpg","originalUrl":"../../../images/1503-ants3.jpg","sha256":"4dc1ae463584077bc5f5120cb6f87b279b899094e8d8aceb3fb9f6d487c3c652"}],"categories":["Array","Brainteaser","Simulation"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"We have a wooden plank of the length `n` **units**. Some ants are walking on the plank, each ant moves with a speed of **1 unit per second**. Some of the ants move to the **left**, the other move to the **right**.\n\nWhen two ants moving in two **different** directions meet at some point, they change their directions and continue moving again. Assume changing directions does not take any additional time.\n\nWhen an ant reaches **one end** of the plank at a time `t`, it falls out of the plank immediately.\n\nGiven an integer `n` and two integer arrays `left` and `right`, the positions of the ants moving to the left and the right, return *the moment when the last ant(s) fall out of the plank*.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1503-last-moment-before-all-ants-fall-out-of-a-plank/1503-ants.jpg","sequence":1,"sha256":"9f26ef75b93b7523dd4c42116abb59641f8e16127bb41f7fa620e6aca0dc9188","type":"image"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Input: n = 4, left = [4,3], right = [0,1]\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: In the image above:\n-The ant at index 0 is named A and going to the right.\n-The ant at index 1 is named B and going to the right.\n-The ant at index 3 is named C and going to the left.\n-The ant at index 4 is named D and going to the left.\nThe last moment when an ant was on the plank is t = 4 seconds. After that, it falls immediately out of the plank. (i.e., We ca