oblems/1537-get-the-maximum-score/1537-sample_1_1893.png]]\n\nInput: nums1 = [2,4,5,8,10], nums2 = [4,6,8,9]\nOutput: 30\nExplanation: Valid paths:\n[2,4,5,8,10], [2,4,5,8,9], [2,4,6,8,9], [2,4,6,8,10],  (starting from nums1)\n[4,6,8,9], [4,5,8,10], [4,5,8,9], [4,6,8,10]    (starting from nums2)\nThe maximum is obtained with the path in green [2,4,6,8,10].\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [1,3,5,7,9], nums2 = [3,5,100]\nOutput: 109\nExplanation: Maximum sum is obtained with the path [1,3,5,100].\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [1,2,3,4,5], nums2 = [6,7,8,9,10]\nOutput: 40\nExplanation: There are no common elements between nums1 and nums2.\nMaximum sum is obtained with the path [6,7,8,9,10].\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums1.length, nums2.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums1[i], nums2[i] <= 10⁷`\n\n- `nums1` and `nums2` are strictly increasing.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/get-the-maximum-score/","problemName":"Get the Maximum Score","problemNumber":1537,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given two **sorted** arrays of distinct integers `nums1` and `nums2`.\n\nA **valid*** ***path** is defined as follows:\n\n- Choose array `nums1` or `nums2` to traverse (from index-0).\n\n- Traverse the current array from left to right.\n\n- If you are reading any value that is present in `nums1` and `nums2` you are allowed to change your path to the other array. (Only one repeated value is considered in the valid path).\n\nThe **score** is defined as the sum of unique values in a valid path.\n\nReturn *the maximum score you can obtain of all possible **valid paths***. Since the answer may be too large, return it modulo `10⁹ + 7`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1537-get-the-maximum-score/1537-sample_1_1893.png","sequence":1,"sha256":"8f5c0e9f537257162670e57c79ddccbcd324896872a623f72e361d8ea4dc0caa","type":"image"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Input: nums1 = [2,4,5,8,10], nums2 = [4,6,8,9]\nOutput: 30\nExplanation: Valid paths:\n[2,4,5,8,10], [2,4,5,8,9], [2,4,6,8,9], [2,4,6,8,10],  (starting from nums1)\n[4,6,8,9], [4,5,8,10], [4,5,8,9], [4,6,8,10]    (starting from nums2)\nThe maximum is obtained with the path in green [2,4,6,8,10].","type":"code"},{"sequence":3,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":4,"text":"Input: nums1 = [1,3,5,7,9], nums2 = [3,5,100]\nOutput: 109\nExplanation: Maximum sum is obtained with the path [1,3,5,100].","type":"code"},{"sequence":5,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":6,"text":"Input: nums1 = [1,2,3,4,5], nums2 = [6,7,8,9,10]\nOutput: 40\nExplanation: There are no common elements between nums1 and nums2.\nMaximum sum is obtained with the path [6,7,8,9,10].","type":"code"},{"sequence":7,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums1.length, nums2.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums1[i], nums2[i] <= 10⁷`\n\n- `nums1` and `nums2` are strictly increasing.","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Hard","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"You are given two **sorted** arrays of distinct integers `nums1` and `nums2`.\n\nA **valid*** ***path** is defined as follows:\n\n- Choose array `nums1` or `nums2` to traverse (from index-0).\n\n- Traverse the current array from left to right.\n\n- If you are reading any value that is present in `nums1` and `nums2` you are allowed to change your path to the other array. (Only one repeated value is considered in the valid path).\n\nThe **score** is defined as the sum of unique values in a valid path.\n\nReturn *the maximum score you can obtain of all possible **valid paths***. Since the answer may be too large, return it modulo `10⁹ + 7`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1537-get-the-maximum-score/1537-sample_1_1893.png]]\n\nInput: nums1 = [2,4,5,8,10], nums2 = [4,6,8,9]\nOutput: 30\nExplanation: Valid paths:\n[2,4,5,8,10], [2,4,5,8,9], [2,4,6,8,9], [2,4,6,8,10],  (starting from nums1)\n[4,6,8,9], [4,5,8,10], [4,5,8,9], [4,6,8,10]    (starting from nums2)\nThe maximum is obtained with the path in green [2,4,6,8,10].\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [1,3,5,7,9], nums2 = [3,5,100]\nOutput: 109\nExplanation: Maximum sum is obtained with the path [1,3,5,100].\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [1,2,3,4,5], nums2 = [6,7,8,9,10]\nOutput: 40\nExplanation: There are no common elements between nums1 and nums2.\nMaximum sum is obtained with the path [6,7,8,9,10].\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= nums1.length, nums2.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums1[i], nums2[i] <= 10⁷`\n\n- `nums1` and `nums2` are strictly increasing.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/get-the-maximum-score/","problemName":"Get the Maximum Score","problemNumber":1537,"problemSlug":"get-the-maximum-score","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":1537,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Math","Interactive"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"We have an integer array `nums`, where all the integers in `nums` are **0** or **1**. You will not be given direct access to the array, instead, you will have an **API** `ArrayReader` which have the following functions:\n\n- `int query(int a, int b, int c, int d)`: where `0 <= a < b < c < d < ArrayReader.length()`. The function returns the distribution of the value of the 4 elements and returns:\n\n- **4 **: if the values of the 4 elements are the same (0 or 1).\n\n- **2** : if three elements have a value equal to 0 and one element has value equal to 1 or vice versa.\n\n- **0 **: if two element have a value equal to 0 and two elements have a value equal to 1.\n\n- `int length()`: Returns the size of the array.\n\nYou are allowed to call `query()` **2 * n times** at most where n is equal to `ArrayReader.length()`.\n\nReturn **any** index of the most frequent value in `nums`, in case of tie, return -1.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums = [0,0,1,0,1,1,1,1]\nOutput: 5\nExplanation: The following calls to the API\nreader.length() // returns 8 because there are 8 elements in the hidden array.\nreader.query(0,1,2,3) // returns 2 this is a query that compares the elements nums[0], nums[1], nums[2], nums[3]\n// Three elements have a value equal to 0 and one element has value equal to 1 or viceversa.\nreader.query(4,5,6,7) // returns 4 because nums[4], nums[5], nums[6], nums[7] have the same value.\nwe can infer that the most frequent value is found in the last 4 elements.\nIndex 2, 4, 6, 7 is also a correct answer.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [0,0,1,1,0]\nOutput: 0","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: nums = [1,0,1,0,1,0,1,0]\nOutput: -1","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `5 <= nums.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= nums[i] <= 1`\n\n**Follow up:** What is the minimum number of calls needed to find the majority element?","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Math","Interactive"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"We have an integer array `nums`, where all the integers in `nums` are **0** or **1**. You will not be given direct access to the array, instead, you will have an **API** `ArrayReader` which have the following functions:\n\n- `int query(int a, int b, int c, int d)`: where `0 <= a < b < c < d < ArrayReader.length()`. The function returns the distribution of the value of the 4 elements and returns:\n\n- **4 **: if the values of the 4 elements are the same (0 or 1).\n\n- **2** : if three elements have a value equal to 0 and one element has value equal to 1 or vice versa.\n\n- **0 **: if two element have a value equal to 0 and two elements have a value equal to 1.\n\n- `int length()`: Returns the size of the array.\n\nYou are allowed to call `query()` **2 * n times** at most where n is equal to `ArrayReader.length()`.\n\nReturn **any** index of the most frequent value in `nums`, in case of tie, return -1.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [0,0,1,0,1,1,1,1]\nOutput: 5\nExplanation: The following calls to the API\nreader.length() // returns 8 because there are 8 elements in the hidden array.\nreader.query(0,1,2,3) // returns 2 this is a query that compares the elements nums[0], nums[1], nums[2], nums[3]\n// Three elements have a value equal to 0 and one element has value equal to 1 or viceversa.\nreader.query(4,5,6,7) // returns 4 because nums[4], nums[5], nums[6], nums[7] have the same value.\nwe can infer that the most frequent value is found in the last 4 elements.\nIndex 2, 4, 6, 7 is also a correct answer.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [0,0,1,1,0]\nOutput: 0\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,0,1,0,1,0,1,0]\nOutput: -1\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `5 <= nums.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= nums[i] <= 1`\n\n**Follow up:** What is the minimum number of calls needed to find the majority element?","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/guess-the-majority-in-a-hidden-array/","problemName":"Guess the Majority in a Hidden Array","problemNumber":1538,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"We have an integer array `nums`, where all the integers in `nums` are **0** or **1**. You will not be given direct access to the array, instead, you will have an **API** `ArrayReader` which have the following functions:\n\n- `int query(int a, int b, int c, int d)`: where `0 <= a < b < c < d < ArrayReader.length()`. The function returns the distribution of the value of the 4 elements and returns:\n\n- **4 **: if the values of the 4 elements are the same (0 or 1).\n\n- **2** : if three elements have a value equal to 0 and one e