,[\"a\",\"a\",\"a\",\"a\"]]\n**Output:** true\n**Explanation: **There are two valid cycles shown in different colors in the image below:\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1559-detect-cycles-in-2d-grid/1559-11.png]]\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1559-detect-cycles-in-2d-grid/1559-22.png]]\n\n**\n\n**Input:** grid = [[\"c\",\"c\",\"c\",\"a\"],[\"c\",\"d\",\"c\",\"c\"],[\"c\",\"c\",\"e\",\"c\"],[\"f\",\"c\",\"c\",\"c\"]]\n**Output:** true\n**Explanation: **There is only one valid cycle highlighted in the image below:\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1559-detect-cycles-in-2d-grid/1559-2.png]]\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1559-detect-cycles-in-2d-grid/1559-3.png]]\n\n**\n\nInput: grid = [[\"a\",\"b\",\"b\"],[\"b\",\"z\",\"b\"],[\"b\",\"b\",\"a\"]]\nOutput: false\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `m == grid.length`\n\n- `n == grid[i].length`\n\n- `1 <= m, n <= 500`\n\n- `grid` consists only of lowercase English letters.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/detect-cycles-in-2d-grid/","problemName":"Detect Cycles in 2D Grid","problemNumber":1559,"problemSlug":"detect-cycles-in-2d-grid","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":1559,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[{"assetIndex":0,"bytes":23228,"contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1560-most-visited-sector-in-a-circular-track/1560-tmp.jpg","originalUrl":"../../../images/1560-tmp.jpg","sha256":"9ffbbd6a3f064b7e82efd8ab4bd1d71e01aaa3c10a88b9f39f502726ac78ebf7"}],"categories":["Array","Simulation"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given an integer `n` and an integer array `rounds`. We have a circular track which consists of `n` sectors labeled from `1` to `n`. A marathon will be held on this track, the marathon consists of `m` rounds. The `i^(th)` round starts at sector `rounds[i - 1]` and ends at sector `rounds[i]`. For example, round 1 starts at sector `rounds[0]` and ends at sector `rounds[1]`\n\nReturn *an array of the most visited sectors* sorted in **ascending** order.\n\nNotice that you circulate the track in ascending order of sector numbers in the counter-clockwise direction (See the first example).\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1560-most-visited-sector-in-a-circular-track/1560-tmp.jpg","sequence":1,"sha256":"9ffbbd6a3f064b7e82efd8ab4bd1d71e01aaa3c10a88b9f39f502726ac78ebf7","type":"image"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Input: n = 4, rounds = [1,3,1,2]\nOutput: [1,2]\nExplanation: The marathon starts at sector 1. The order of the visited sectors is as follows:\n1 --> 2 --> 3 (end of round 1) --> 4 --> 1 (end of round 2) --> 2 (end of round 3 and the marathon)\nWe can see that both sectors 1 and 2 are visited twice and they are the most visited sectors. Sectors 3 and 4 are visited only once.","type":"code"},{"sequence":3,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":4,"text":"Input: n = 2, rounds = [2,1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2]\nOutput: [2]","type":"code"},{"sequence":5,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":6,"text":"Input: n = 7, rounds = [1,3,5,7]\nOutput: [1,2,3,4,5,6,7]","type":"code"},{"sequence":7,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= n <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= m <= 100`\n\n- `rounds.length == m + 1`\n\n- `1 <= rounds[i] <= n`\n\n- `rounds[i] != rounds[i + 1]` for `0 <= i < m`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Simulation"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given an integer `n` and an integer array `rounds`. We have a circular track which consists of `n` sectors labeled from `1` to `n`. A marathon will be held on this track, the marathon consists of `m` rounds. The `i^(th)` round starts at sector `rounds[i - 1]` and ends at sector `rounds[i]`. For example, round 1 starts at sector `rounds[0]` and ends at sector `rounds[1]`\n\nReturn *an array of the most visited sectors* sorted in **ascending** order.\n\nNotice that you circulate the track in ascending order of sector numbers in the counter-clockwise direction (See the first example).\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1560-most-visited-sector-in-a-circular-track/1560-tmp.jpg]]\n\nInput: n = 4, rounds = [1,3,1,2]\nOutput: [1,2]\nExplanation: The marathon starts at sector 1. The order of the visited sectors is as follows:\n1 --> 2 --> 3 (end of round 1) --> 4 --> 1 (end of round 2) --> 2 (end of round 3 and the marathon)\nWe can see that both sectors 1 and 2 are visited twice and they are the most visited sectors. Sectors 3 and 4 are visited only once.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: n = 2, rounds = [2,1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2]\nOutput: [2]\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: n = 7, rounds = [1,3,5,7]\nOutput: [1,2,3,4,5,6,7]\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= n <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= m <= 100`\n\n- `rounds.length == m + 1`\n\n- `1 <= rounds[i] <= n`\n\n- `rounds[i] != rounds[i + 1]` for `0 <= i < m`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/most-visited-sector-in-a-circular-track/","problemName":"Most Visited Sector in  a Circular Track","problemNumber":1560,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given an integer `n` and an integer array `rounds`. We have a circular track which consists of `n` sectors labeled from `1` to `n`. A marathon will be held on this track, the marathon consists of `m` rounds. The `i^(th)` round starts at sector `rounds[i - 1]` and ends at sector `rounds[i]`. For example, round 1 starts at sector `rounds[0]` and ends at sector `rounds[1]`\n\nReturn *an array of the most visited sectors* sorted in **ascending** order.\n\nNotice that you circulate the track in ascending order of sector numbers in the counter-clockwise direction (See the first example).\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","conte